{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ef92aa9c-a050-4403-8078-500c5fce9913","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a dotnet tool:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n- **`PackAsTool`** — marks the project as a dotnet tool.\n- **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users invoke (e.g., `my-mcp-server`).\n- **`OutputType` must be `Exe`** — tools must be console apps.\n- Since you use **stdio transport**, the tool just reads stdin/writes stdout — no extra config needed there.\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push (get an API key from nuget.org)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server\n```\n\nWould you like me to create the project or update an existing `.csproj`?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6e6d5978-097b-44b1-840d-20e90df4e030","outputTokens":447,"requestId":"7FCE:2941EA:43D960C:4A75D08:69F15B98"},"id":"0cf75ca9-f9ad-46a7-b0ee-ccf692abc6c9","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:15:13.594Z","parentId":"8e361923-7fec-4af4-94b7-435c409512bb"}
